article.description:
Lisa Leslie led five starters in double
figures with 25 points and the Los Angeles Sparks overpowered the
Utah Starzz 103-77 Saturday to sweep the Western Conference finals
and advance to the WNBA championship.
article.headline: Record-setting Sparks waltz into finals

images.name: Leslie_rebound 020824 inline
images.caption: Lisa Leslie pulls down one of her six rebounds for the Sparks.

article.linkText: Sparks pile up points, reach WNBA final
article.story:
Saturday, Aug. 24
Utah simply isn't going to win when Natalie Williams and Margo Dydek combine for just nine rebounds. But in Sunday's 103-77 loss to Los Angeles, Williams didn't score until the second half and finished with only seven points and four rebounds, and Dydek tallied six points and five rebounds.

The one thing that has been really obvious this postseason is how important the 4 position is in the WNBA. Everything runs through the 4, whether it's the fast break or ball reversal, and some of the most versatile athletes in the league play the position. The offense revolves around the 4, and that's where a lot of matchup problems have occurred.

Sunday, Dydek got stuck guarding either Lisa Leslie or DeLisha Milton, and it was physically impossible for the 7-foot-2 Dydek to go out and chase those two Sparks. Dydek was constantly playing away from the basket, and that was the biggest exploited area on the floor as both Milton (19 points, seven rebounds) and Leslie (25 points, six rebounds) flourished. Milton had a great series, and came off the bench to average 18 points a game.

L.A.'s balance (five players in double figures) and ability to take care of the ball (only eight turnovers) were also big keys. And the Sparks, who have definitely cranked up their intensity, are passing the ball extremely well. They dished out 31 assists on 80 points, a phenomenal stat that means L.A. constantly made the extra pass to keep Utah's defense off balance.
LOS ANGELES -- The Los Angeles Sparks were so dominating, they needed just one half to put the game away. Lisa Leslie scored 25 points and the Sparks overpowered the Utah Starzz 103-77 Saturday to sweep the Western Conference finals and advance to the WNBA championship. "We ran into a team that is clicking on all cylinders and just shooting the ball as well as just about any team I've ever seen,'' Utah coach Candi Harvey said. The Sparks' 103 points was a WNBA playoff record, topping the 101 points they scored against Phoenix in the first round on Aug. 13, 2000. After jumping out to a 15-point halftime lead, the Sparks continued the rout in the second half and opened a 30-point lead. Besides Leslie, DeLisha Milton had 19 points, Mwadi Mabika had 15 points and nine rebounds, Tamecka Dixon had 15 points and rookie Nikki Teasley added 11 points and nine assists. "This is the best I've ever seen this team play,'' said Sparks coach Michael Cooper, who has been with the team for 3½ years. "They understand now what it takes not only to become champions, but to repeat as champions.'' Defense of their league title begins Thursday against the Eastern Conference champion. New York beat Washington 96-79 on Saturday night to force a deciding third game in that series. "New York-L.A. sounds the best, but Washington has been doing great,'' Leslie said of a potential matchup. "At this point, it's just about the championship. Our main goal right now is to get Game 1.'' Fans buoyed by the prospect of the Sparks winning a second consecutive championship chanted "back to back'' when Los Angeles led by 21 points with 13 minutes to play. The Sparks shot 51 percent, had 31 assists and outscored the Starzz 14-0 on fast-break points. "We came out aggressive and we wanted to jump on them first,'' Leslie said. "We played great team defense, that's where championships are won. Offensively, we played excellent as far as moving the ball and finding open players.'' The Starzz were completely outplayed in the second half, when they never made a run and fell behind against the WNBA's highest-scoring playoff team. "They are so talented and they are peaking and pulling together at the right time,'' Utah guard Jennifer Azzi said. "You can't stop them one-on-one, so it has to be a team effort defensively. That's something that we didn't have, so they got on a roll and they got momentum. When you have that much talent, it's just hard to stop.'' Adrienne Goodson and Azzi scored 16 points each to lead the Starzz, who knocked off four-time WNBA champion Houston in the first round. Azzi tied Cynthia Cooper's league playoff record with 12 assists. "I certainly got more aggressive in the second half. No one else was doing it,'' Azzi said. Margo Dydek, Utah's 7-foot center, was ineffective, with six points and five rebounds. Natalie Williams had seven points on 2-of-7 shooting. Los Angeles put the game away in the first half with a 35-13 run that produced a 44-29 halftime lead. After shooting 7 of 19 to start the game, the Sparks trailed 16-10. Milton started the game-breaking run as the Sparks scored eight in a row to tie the game at 18. Then they rattled off 16 consecutive points for a 34-18 lead. "D is just an energizer,'' Cooper said. "Inserting her into the (starting) lineup, we wanted that energy starting from the beginning. She gave it to us, with good defense on Natalie and hitting her jump shots.''
